   <h1>Re: [VB] re: classic insurance</h1>
   <b>Old Volks &lt;general_at_oldvolks_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2004-09-17 05:23:17+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>  I have all my vehicles with Farmers ( all my VW's are liability only and cost 100 or so per year each) except my wifes 
65 beetle, it's with Pullman. I just got turned down again on another bus by Pullmans, they are getting stricter and 
stricter as to what they will cover, specially at replacement value. They now go by Old Car Guide or something like that 
and if your model isn't listed it's hard to get stated value, or even current market. They are also getting very picky on 
APPEARANCE of the vehicle, my DD is faded paint 7 years old, was turned down because, and yes this is what they told 
me "It isn't shinney enough". My agent said polish it and it will go through, HUHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH. So next week it's 
WD40 time (yes it can make a dull bus shine), shoot some new pics (now they want a portfolio of pics where as 1 use 
to be enough) and I'm sure it will get covered, but not for near what I have invested!!!!!!!! Even with reciepts, a liget 
apprasial and comps will they cover it for what I asked.


ronnie
Old Volks of AZ
www.type2parts_dot_com

On Thu, 16 Sep 2004 21:31 , Richard Lenzmeier <dicklenznd_at_yahoo_dot_com> sent:

>The listees are correct in that GEICO will write policies for our older
>VWs, but just liability, not collision or comprehensive. Comp insurance
>is written by a subsidiary of GEICO, American Collectors, but I didn't
>check with them to get a quote, but I will before I renew my Hagerty
>policy next year. I can't go with just liability--after thirty years
>out of a bus, I don't want an accident to keep me out of one while I
>save up for repairs. I am sorry about the misinformation.
>
>Richard L
>Fargo, ND
>1964 Standard Microbus
>1956 Euro market Type I</pre>


